04204nam a22005175i 9780674985124DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749851247 a10.4159/97806749851242doi  a(DE-B1597)501477  a(OCoLC)1028732095  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF1262b.H37 2018eb 7aLAW1160002bisacsh04a342.7308/582231 aHartzog, Woodrow, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrivacy’s Blueprint :bThe Battle to Control the Design of New Technologies /cWoodrow Hartzog. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (322 p.) :b20 halftones, 1 chart  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Designing Our Privacy Away -- tPART ONE. The Case for Taking Design Seriously in Privacy Law -- tWhy Design is Everything -- tPrivacy Law’s Design Gap -- tPART TWO. A Design Agenda for Privacy Law -- tPrivacy Values in Design -- tSetting Boundaries for Design -- tA Tool Kit for Privacy Design -- tPART THEREE. Applying Privacy’s Blueprint -- tSocial Media -- tHide and Seek Technologies -- tThe Internet of Things -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tCredits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery day, Internet users interact with technologies designed to undermine their privacy. Social media apps, surveillance technologies, and the Internet of Things are all built in ways that make it hard to guard personal information. And the law says this is okay because it is up to users to protect themselves—even when the odds are deliberately stacked against them. In Privacy’s Blueprint, Woodrow Hartzog pushes back against this state of affairs, arguing that the law should require software and hardware makers to respect privacy in the design of their products. Current legal doctrine treats technology as though it were value-neutral: only the user decides whether it functions for good or ill. But this is not so. As Hartzog explains, popular digital tools are designed to expose people and manipulate users into disclosing personal information. Against the often self-serving optimism of Silicon Valley and the inertia of tech evangelism, Hartzog contends that privacy gains will come from better rules for products, not users. The current model of regulating use fosters exploitation. Privacy’s Blueprint aims to correct this by developing the theoretical underpinnings of a new kind of privacy law responsive to the way people actually perceive and use digital technologies. The law can demand encryption. It can prohibit malicious interfaces that deceive users and leave them vulnerable. It can require safeguards against abuses of biometric surveillance. It can, in short, make the technology itself worthy of our trust.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aData protectionxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDesign and technologyzUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 7aLAW / Privacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067498512440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674985124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674985124.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles